Furthermore, the repression of this multiplication has an effect on the development of so-called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Czech Academy of Sciences, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to a way to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are a bore, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt assembly.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all drugs used so far and that’s why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers’ work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their virus protein bonds.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-wall cages are formed by the bore, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
