HIV protease is a HIV protein that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV division caused by HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, the spread of the virus into the patient’s body will also be stopped, researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic and Biochemistry of the Czech Republic Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (cf. table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
