The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivoral dinosaurs: this bipede measured about 2 meters long for 1.50 meters high, its behind limbs were powerful, his sleeping skull was equipped with sharp and turned teeth, his short arms ended with sickle claws, and he had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as reported by Sertling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and his colleagues in the Science magazine on Thursday, the Tawa Hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
