Not all experts in paleontology share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander from the University of Bonn does not find that this discovery is particularly spectacular, but he says that it confirms certain theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, which makes the classification of all early dinosaurs very difficult.
Experts wonder, among others, when the Saurians were divided into three major evolution groups: the theropodes (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaure and the velociraptor later appeared and which descend the birds, the sauropodes, the long-neck quadrupedes, and those who are their relatives and the ornithic herbivorures.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa is one of the first theropodes.
This species presents an interesting report of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found indications that lead to think that the Tawa hallae had small air bags in its bones at the skull level, just like birds that are descendants of the theropodes.
These small air pockets facilitate the breathing of birds compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, Tawa is one of the oldest theropodes with small air bags in its bones.
As the related line of immense sauropods also possessed air bags and a light bone, it may be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
