A psychosis is a serious, painful illness but also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the form of so-called oniroid experience, a particular form of the change of consciousness awakened by dream.
Oniroid lives are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot distinguish from the dream even when he is in a state of awakening.
The state of oniroid consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully aware, experience a motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that affects his life, by his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental limit between dream and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change in the world takes place, but the real situation is represented in imagination.
In fact, it is an intense form of means and interpretation, in an intolerable situation in itself, an organizational capacity that is given to us, men, to not fall into the nonetheless of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in memories.
The Zurichian Peter Cornelius Classen, art historian, also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Change of Heart" as a safeguarding action of the soul.
He is 49 years old, when his conscious departs for a journey of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is condemned to remain immobile in reanimation.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created from all parts, visits foreign places, travels in time. He sees himself as an old man alied in a railway sanatorium, a robot with his head watching his health.
He lives in the middle age among nobles who manufacture blood drugs.
He is kidnapped by a bicycle Greek who takes him to his country, he surfing with his hospital bed in the Alps snow and meets a Korean mafia.
He absorbs completely into this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner travels are fundamentally distinguished from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes by describing what he has experienced.
In contrast to dreams, the memories from mental trips are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and more intense than real life.
The intensity of this experience broke the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oniroid deliries, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in a standby state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten "can cause a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite enriching.
