75% of mothers who work had professional problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women in young generations who want to be mothers.
This is what reveals the study "Women's Fecundity and Professional Career in Spain", conducted by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no doubt: 75% of mothers who worked have seen their career limited due to motherhood.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of occupied job.
Those who do not have any activity outside the home, work part-time, or have unstable work, become couple earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, repeat entry into life as a couple and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women aged 35 to 49 years of fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in couples. This figure grows to 4.1 among women working in the public sector. "This data shows that women with a stable job needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to repulse the union and arrival of children.
Furthermore, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of beginning of common life,” explains the researcher at CSIC Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that exaggerates the difference from the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the investigation, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child later.
The difference also remains among women of one generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years old, those who studied elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years average, respectively.
Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have done elementary studies get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have done a medium or higher level studies reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child,” says Mrs. Delgado.
