Emergency braking aid is now mandatory
As this happened with the ABS brake anti-blocking system and as this will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency brake aid systems will constitute a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory for newly registered tourist cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of deficiency has been set until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the European Union is to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, although by its mode of action it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver's foot hit.
But it doesn’t always maintain pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all its strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in revanch, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance the car needed to stop.
According to a EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 mortal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: one in four injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects the obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to slightly acting on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps it by increasing pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exercises the maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
